## The two rules that actually matter

### 1. Never silently fall back to your own model

If you pass a `model` slug the Task tool doesn't recognize, the tool **rejects the call and returns the current list of valid slugs.** When that happens:

- **Pick a valid slug from the list the tool just gave you and retry.**
- **NEVER respond by dropping the `model` parameter and re-running on your own model.** A subagent that quietly runs on the parent model gives you the same blind spots as doing it yourself — the entire point of multi-model coverage is gone, and you won't notice. This already happened once: a "multi-model" audit silently ran on one model the whole time.
- The tool's accepted list is the real source of truth. If this roster is stale, trust the tool and update this file.

### 2. Different jobs that need diversity use DIFFERENT families

When a protocol says to run N subagents on the same task (auditing the same area, reviewing the same work, proposing competing designs):

- Use **N different model families.** Two Opus variants do NOT count as two families — they share blind spots.
- **Never use the same slug twice for the same job.**
- **Diversity beats power.** A cheap model from a different family catches more than a second expensive model from the same family. Don't default to the biggest/most expensive models; spread across families.

### 3. Record which model actually produced each artifact

When subagents write deliverables (audit reports, architecture proposals, review findings), the **orchestrator** records the model slug it assigned, in the artifact (e.g. a header line `Model: gpt-5.5-extra-high`). Do NOT rely on a subagent self-labeling its own model -- a file named `ARCHITECTURE-PROPOSAL-CLAUDE.md` or a "by Claude Opus" byline proves nothing about what actually ran. If you can't say which real model produced two "independent" proposals, you don't have two independent proposals.

## Multi-model debate to consensus

Use this whenever two (or more) subagents have each returned a competing proposal for the SAME decision and those proposals must converge into ONE answer (the clearest case is the two architecture proposals in a rebuild). **Do not let a single converger silently pick a winner.** The proposing models argue it out, round by round, until they agree.

Use it for real trade-offs (architecture, structure, tech stack, data model). Do NOT use it to relitigate things that are fixed — e.g. which features to keep is non-negotiable; debate resolves HOW to build, never WHAT exists.

### The same-models exception (important)

This is the ONE place you deliberately **reuse the same model** that wrote each proposal. Each model defends ITS OWN proposal, so every round you re-spawn the same slug for each side — Proposal A is always argued by the model that wrote A, Proposal B by the model that wrote B. ("You said X, the other model said Y" only means something if the original author answers.) Everywhere else you rotate families; here you keep them fixed. Attribution still applies: record which slug argued which side.

### Each round

1. The orchestrator extracts the **open points of disagreement** from the latest proposals/rebuttals — a short, specific list.
2. For EACH side, spawn its model with the **full running debate context**. Subagents are stateless -- a fresh spawn remembers NOTHING from prior rounds -- so every turn must include: the two original proposals, the **entire DEBATE-LOG so far** (every prior round's defend/concede/third-option exchange), the list of points already RESOLVED *with the agreed answer for each* (so a model can't reopen settled ground or re-propose a rejected option), the current open-points list, and the canonical inventory/audit. Without this, the models lose the thread, repeat themselves, and never converge. (If the log grows large over many rounds, you may compress the RESOLVED section to a tight summary, but pass the open-point exchanges in full.) Prompt each:
   > "Here is your position and the other model's position on these open points: [list]. For EACH open point do exactly ONE of: (a) DEFEND your position with concrete reasons (cite the inventory / audit / build history), (b) CONCEDE the other approach is better and say why, or (c) PROPOSE A THIRD OPTION not yet on the table. Be specific. End with two lists: points you now consider RESOLVED, and points still OPEN."
3. Collect both responses. A point is **closed** when both sides land on the same answer (one conceded, or both adopted a third option). Update the open-points list to only what's still contested.

Repeat, feeding each model the other's newest rebuttal, until one of:

- **Consensus** — the open-points list is empty; both models agree on everything. This is the goal.
- **Stalemate** — a full round produces no movement (no concession, no new third option, the same two positions). Don't loop forever. The orchestrator resolves each remaining point: the **canonical audit/inventory wins** if one side contradicts it; otherwise pick the option with the stronger stated reasoning and RECORD why; if it's a genuine product/judgment call the user would care about, surface it to the user instead of deciding silently.

**Round cap:** if you hit ~3–4 rounds without consensus, treat it as a stalemate and resolve as above. Endless debate burns tokens without converging.

### Record it

Write the debate to a log (e.g. `DEBATE-LOG.md`, or a section of the plan): every round, what each side did (defend / concede / third option), what closed, what stayed open, and the final consensus (or the orchestrator's tie-break with reasons). Keep model attribution per round. **The converged plan must reflect the consensus — not one model's unilateral pick.** Guardrail: the consensus must not contradict the canonical audit/inventory.

## Quick self-check before you spawn

- [ ] Did I set `model` explicitly on every Task call?
- [ ] For a multi-subagent job, are they on different families (no repeats)?
- [ ] If a slug got rejected, did I pick another valid one (and NOT fall back to my own model)?
- [ ] Does each prompt contain all the context the subagent needs, since it can't see this chat?
- [ ] For deliverables, did I record the real (orchestrator-assigned) model on the artifact rather than trusting a self-label?
- [ ] If I'm converging competing proposals, did I run the **debate-to-consensus loop** (same models defend their own proposals, round by round) instead of letting one converger pick a winner?
